observations.recommendation:
We recommended and reiterated the following to Management:

Require the Inventory Committee to conduct annual inventory-taking of all PPE and timely submit the RPCPPE for all PPEs together with the RPCLRN of the LGU within the prescribed period;

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer, being the Property Officer in lieu of the absence of the GSO, to prepare and maintain the Local Road Inventory Map and Property Cards for each type of properties as basis for reconciliation with the PPE accounts with the accounting records;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain, in relation to the local road networks of the LGU, LRNLC, including the regular property ledger cards, also as basis for reconciliation with the GL account balances and with the property records;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to immediately transfer the completed PPEs recorded in the TF to the GF and to effect the necessary adjusting entries for the prior years’ depreciation expense as well as the reclassification of the erroneous recording of assets and expenses as PPE to avoid overstatement of PPE and government equity accounts;

Require the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to make a final reconciliation of their respective records and avail the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, strictly in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006, particularly on the disposition and derecognition of non-existing/missing PPE and adjust the books accordingly, in order to come up with reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability; 

Require the Inventory Committee to immediately request authority to dispose those identified unserviceable and obsolete PPE and drop from the books the book value thereof upon approval in accordance with existing accounting and auditing rules and regulations; and

Assess its existing organizational structure and consider the appointment of a permanent GSO to perform the duly designated duties and responsibilities effectively and efficiently.

We recommended that Management require:

11. The Inventory Committee or the Supply Officer-Designate to prepare and submit the duly accomplished RPCI;

12. The Municipal Accountant to properly record the purchases of inventories in the appropriate inventory accounts and the consumption thereof as expense, upon receipt of SSMI of a given period, to ensure the proper monitoring, controlling and issuances of inventory items;

13. The Supply Officer-Designate and the Municipal Accountant to maintain updated Supplies Ledger Cards and Stock Cards required of them; and

14. Supply Officer-Designate and the Municipal Accountant to conduct periodic reconciliation of their records and make adjustments, when necessary, particularly the write-off of non-existing inventory items, to reflect the true balance of the Inventory and Expense Accounts in the Financial Statements.

We recommended and reiterated that Management:
Require the Inventory Committee to conduct the actual physical count of all PPE in accordance with the MNGAS for LGUs, COA Circular No. 2015-008 and COA Circular No. 2020-006 to properly prepare and submit the prescribed RPCPPE and RPCLRN within the prescribed period;
Instruct the Property/Supply Officer-Designate, in lieu of the absence of the GSO, to prepare and maintain the Local Road Inventory Map, updated Property Cards and Property Acknowledgment Receipts;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
i. 	Prepare and maintain, in relation to the local road networks of the LGU, LRNLC, including the regular property ledger cards, also as basis for reconciliation with the General Ledger (GL) account balances and with the property records;
ii. 	Adjust the items erroneously recorded as PPE to the appropriate accounts;
iii. 	Prepare a detailed lapsing schedule in computing the yearly depreciation expense and adjust the books for depreciation expenses erroneously computed and recognized in the previous years; and
Require the Property/Supply Officer-Designate and Municipal Accountant to make a final reconciliation of their respective records and avail the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, strictly in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006, particularly on the disposition and derecognition of non-existing/missing PPE and adjust the books accordingly, in order to come up with reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended that Management:
Require the concerned officials to furnish the Audit Team copies of the MOA on all fertilizer loan granted to farmer-debtors;
Require the concerned officials to prepare an updated schedule and individual SLs of the subject loans receivables, indicating the individual borrowers and the amount due and demandable as of report date to substantiate the balance reported in the FS and facilitate effective monitoring of balances of every account;
Provide the Treasury Office a copy of this schedule which will serve as their basis in the enforcement of collection of the farmer-debtor’s unpaid loans, if still workable; and
Revisit the MOA and consider writing-off the uncollected loans to farmers who have suffered loss due to force majeure events in accordance with the terms and conditions of the contract.

We recommended that Management require:
The Property/Supply Officer-Designate and other concerned Heads of Offices to immediately submit to the Accounting Office, copy furnished the Audit Team, the documents supporting the issuance, consumption or distribution of various inventories held for consumption and distribution;
The Municipal Accountant to properly record the purchase of inventories in the appropriate inventory accounts and the issuance, consumption and distribution thereof as expense upon receipt of RIS and SSMI of a given period and supported with a duly accomplished and fully accounted distribution list and proof of actual distribution together with other required documents;
The Inventory Committee to conduct the required physical count of all supplies and materials and submit the RPCI; and
The Accounting Office and the Property Office to maintain complete and updated Stock Ledger Cards and Stock Cards, respectively.

We recommended that Management direct the following offices:
The Municipal Assessor’s Office to comply with prompt submission of assessment roll to the Treasury Office for newly assessed or reassessed properties before the 31st day of December each year;
The Municipal Treasurer’s Office to:
Properly prepare the taxpayers’ index card showing relevant information on tax delinquencies of each taxpayer;
Regularly update the same upon receipt of the assessment roll and upon determination of tax due and collectible for the year;
Prepare the duly certified list showing the names of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year to be submitted to the Accounting Office; and
Prepare the certified list of all RPT delinquencies to be submitted to the Sanggunian concerned with a request for assistance in the enforcement of the remedies for colleciton; and
The Municipal Accountant to observe due diligence in recording transactions by using the appropriate accounts under COA Circular No. 2015-009, following the accounting entries/procedures for RPT and SET transactions and to reconcile the affected accounts and effect the necessary adjusting/correcting entries to present fairly the balances in the FS.

We recommended that Management require the MSWDO to thoroughly conduct the assessment of clients requesting financial assistance out of the AICS program to:
Ascertain the eligibility of the client to request assistance on his/her behalf or for another beneficiary;
Ensure that the authority of the client to avail the assistance in behalf of another person/beneficiary is clearly established in the assessment form and supporting documents;
Ensure that the reasonable and allowed amount of assistance is granted;
Ensure that clients availing a particular assistance more than once may be granted only within the limit prescribed by the LGU’s guidelines in line with DSWD MC No. 24;
Ensure that the kind of assistance availed of is under the LGU’s AICS program and DSWD MC No. 24, otherwise, accordingly refer the clients to other assistance/services that may be accessed from other LGU resources or institutions/networks; and
Ensure the existence of adequate documentary requirements before the issuance of the Certificate of Eligibility.

We recommended that Management require the concerned officials to:
Explain for the deficiencies noted therein;
Conduct meticulous procurement planning and proper determination of the mode of procurement to be used which must be indicated in the APP;
Strictly abide with the procedural guidelines for the appropriate alternative mode of procurement;
Henceforth, ensure that all procurements must be made from technically, legally and financially capable suppliers of goods and services; and
Ensure completeness of documentary requirements for the appropriate alternative mode of procurement and specific documents required for the procurement of drugs and medicines and radio communication equipment.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Exert effort in reconciling and establishing the unremitted trust collections from prior years’ transactions and once established, accordingly remit the same to the respective government agencies;
Prepare and maintain SLs on the composition of the balances of Due to BIR for withheld taxes on compensation and government money payments, and Dues to GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth for premiums, contributions and loan amortization, and other subsidiary accounts, as needed;
Appropriately charge and collect from the suppliers/contractors/employees to whom the overremittance of withheld taxes, premiums or contributions pertain; and
Henceforth, ensure the conduct of monthly reconciliation of remittances against withheld amounts to prevent recurrence of unreconciled or inaccurate remittance of balances.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the concerned officials to:

Install controls on the monitoring of issuance and consumption of fuel, such as reconciliation of all related reports, to ascertain that expenditures for gasoline/diesel are valid, reasonable, effectively controlled and properly accounted for in compliance with the rules and regulations on fuel consumption;

Prepare and submit regularly to the Office of the Auditor, within 10 days of the following month, the properly accomplished and approved Report of Fuel Consumption, Monthly Report of Official Travels and Generator Monthly Report or its equivalent;

Ensure that all payments are supported with complete and properly accomplished and approved Driver’s Trip Tickets, RIS and the required monthly reports; and

Strictly adhere with the provisions of RA No. 9184 on the procurement through direct contracting, or the appropriate alternative mode of procurement, in order to promote economy and efficiency and to ensure that the most advantageous price for the Government is obtained.

We reiterated our recommendation that Management:
Require the Inventory Committee to conduct an annual physical inventory-taking of all PPE and submit a complete RPCPPE within the deadline;
Direct the Designated Supply Officer to practice the periodic reconciliation with the accounting records to immediately detect errors/irregularities;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to transfer the completed/acquired PPE booked in the Trust Fund to the General Fund books. Also, ensure monthly recognition of depreciation expense of all the PPE accounts, update the accumulated depreciation accounts and record the adjustments in the government equity account for the prior years’ depreciation expenses; and
Direct the Inventory Committee to exert utmost effort in conducting the activities relative to the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances.

We recommended that Management:
Require the BAC to strictly adhere to the provisions of RA No. 9184 and its IRR in the procurement process.  Every detail of the procurement documents must be reviewed as to its correctness, particularly the details of the Approved Budget for the Contract and the dates of NOA, Contract, NTP and other vital documents supporting the procurement;
Impose Liquidated Damages on the project having negative slippage of one tenth of one per cent for every day of delay based on the unperformed portion of the contract;
Require the contractors to post warranty security for all completed and accepted projects; and
Henceforth, cancel the award of contract for those winning bidders who were unable to post Performance Security but entered into a contract within the allowable number days as provided in RA No. 9184 and its IRR.

The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer conduct review and analysis of their respective records (GL and Cashbook) to determine the nature of each account and come up with reconciled and correct balances of the Cash in Bank accounts for all funds, reconcile them with the records of the depository banks (BS), and prepare adjustments, if warranted;

The Municipal Accountant prepare Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to take up all valid reconciling items in the BRS already determined as book error and to exert extra effort to reconcile BRS of prior periods; and

The Municipal Accountant prepare and regularly submit the BRS to the Auditor for us to be able to conduct timely review/verification.

Immediately send demand letters to officials and employees, who have outstanding cash advances as of December 31, 2020, to settle the overdue amounts within a specific period. Otherwise, effect the withholding of their salaries pursuant to 5.1.3 of  Circular No. 97-002 until such time that the cash advances are fully settled; 

Direct the designated AOs to strictly comply with the rules and regulations particularly on the liquidation of cash advances, within the prescribed period to ensure that all disbursements are recorded in the books in the appropriate time/period;

Prepare a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) for the liquidation of the cash advances for Intelligence/Confidential Fund which already have transmittal letter duly received by COA Central Office thru COA – Intelligence and Confidential Audit Unit (ICFAU); and

File request for authority to write-off dormant or long outstanding unliquidated cash advances, if necessary, to the Office of the Auditor, pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

Conduct a systematic and realistic forecasting of revenue taking into account prior years’ experience and statistics as aide in setting targets;
Provide for the targets on income accounts that did not have projections which must be based on statistics, prior years’ experience and future expectation; and
The Municipal Budget Officer correct the coding of projected revenues to align and conform with the Standard Chart of Accounts promulgated by the Commission on Audit pursuant to COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015.

We recommended that Management:

In collaboration with the Local School Board, ensure that the total share on the additional 1% tax on real property from previous years is completely appropriated in the preparation of the succeeding years SEF Annual Budget to facilitate achieving the goals of education as provided by the Constitution;
Ensure that the ₱331,153.58 as well as other prior years’ idle Special Education Fund be appropriated immediately for priority projects;
Require the Municipal budget Officer to see to it that balance of the unappropriated surplus during the year be immediately released to the Local School Board for inclusion in the budget of the ensuing year; and
Require also the LSB to strictly comply with the requirements of Section 272 of RA No. 7160 and DepED, DBM and DILG Joint Circular No. 1 s. 2017 in identifying the PPAs that reflect an equitable distribution of the mandated priority expenses and maximize the implementation of the identified programs to ensure efficient utilization of the fund so that its objectives are fully achieved.
